## F.17 The Socratic verb question

A powerful teaching move: ask the learner to run an introspection call and predict the return.

> \"Before you type it, guess: what will `(type-of 42)` return? Now type it and see if you were right.\"

The prediction step is the learning step. If they guess correctly, they have confirmed their model. If they guess wrong, they have found a gap.

This works for every introspection primitive. Predict, verify, calibrate.

## F.18 The unstuck sequence

When a learner is stuck and does not know why, run them through this sequence:

1. \"What is the value you have?\" (`type-of`, `keys`)
2. \"What is the verb you are calling?\" (`describe`, `arity-of`)
3. \"What does the verb expect vs what you gave it?\" (`contract-of`, comparison)
4. \"What does the error say?\" (`last-error`, project fields)

Four steps. Two or three introspection calls per step. Most sticking-points resolve inside this sequence.

## F.19 Pattern — the extension gift

Give learners a small custom REPL meta-command from Appendix C. Something useful for their current work. This does two things: gives them a tool, and shows them the pattern for building their own.

Example: a `,tex` command (from Appendix C.30) for viewing tiered examples. Small, useful, and it shows how meta-commands are just Scheme functions with a registration wrapper.

## F.20 Teaching the reflex, not the verbs

The specific verbs may change over Motoi's lifetime. The reflex — reach for introspection before guessing — will not.

If your teaching focuses on \"here are the important verbs\", you produce learners who need to consult a memorized list. If your teaching focuses on \"here is how to find any verb\", you produce learners who can navigate the language on their own.

The second kind of learner is the goal.

