## F.26 Deep-seed — a full teaching session example

Session goal: teach a learner what `fold` does.

**Step 1** — the guided lookup.
Teacher: \"Have you used fold before?\"
Learner: \"I have heard of it.\"
Teacher: \"Try `(describe 'fold)` at the REPL. What comes back?\"
Learner: [types] \"It says fold combines a list into a single value.\"
Teacher: \"Good. What is its arity?\"
Learner: \"3.\"
Teacher: \"So it takes three arguments. What are they?\"
Learner: \"The contract says (procedure any list) → any.\"
Teacher: \"Right. Now `(examples-of 'fold)`.\"
Learner: [types] \"There is a novice example: (fold + 0 '(1 2 3 4 5)).\"
Teacher: \"Try it.\"
Learner: [types] \"15.\"
Teacher: \"Predict: what would (fold * 1 '(1 2 3 4)) return?\"
Learner: \"24?\"
Teacher: [types] \"Yes.\"

Three minutes. The learner knows what fold does, has run two working examples, and has practiced the introspection reflex four times. All without a lecture.

## F.27 Deep-seed — the confidence build

Learners often lack confidence in exploring a new language. Introspection helps.

**Bad experience:** open unfamiliar code, do not know what a verb does, feel lost.

**Good experience:** open unfamiliar code, see an unfamiliar verb, run `(describe 'that-verb)`, get an answer, move on.

The second experience builds confidence because the tools always work. There is always a way to find out. Learners who internalize this reflex stop feeling lost — they feel like they have a compass.

Teachers can accelerate this by explicitly saying it: \"Whenever you see a verb you do not recognize, you can always describe it. That never fails.\"

Then let the learner experience it a few times. The confidence grows on its own.

## F.28 Deep-seed — for the kid in North Georgia

A note from the memory doctrine: Motoi is for the kid who needs all the verbs in one place. Introspection is what makes that kid's access to those verbs frictionless.

For teachers of kids: model the introspection reflex from day one. Do not have them memorize verb lists. Have them learn `(help 'verb)`. That habit will carry them further than any lecture on specific verbs.

The kid who learns to ask the language questions is the kid who grows up into a programmer who does not need to be told anything.

