## F.42 Deep-seed — introspection and self-teaching

Every programmer is their own teacher some of the time. The introspection reflex works for self-teaching the same way it works for tutoring another person.

When you encounter a Motoi feature you have not used, do not read the reference cover to cover. Do this instead:

1. `(apropos \"related-keyword\")` — enumerate candidates
2. `(describe 'top-candidate)` — quick sense
3. `(examples-of 'top-candidate)` — see it used
4. Try it in a small experiment
5. `(help 'top-candidate)` for the full record if needed

Five steps. All introspection. All self-directed. This is how a working Motoi programmer learns new features on the fly, without a course, without a mentor.

## F.43 Deep-seed — the pedagogy compounds

Introspection habits compound. A programmer who has the reflex for a year has explored more of the language than a programmer who has the reflex for a week. The gap widens over time.

For teachers: get the reflex started early. It grows on its own.

For learners: use it every day. It becomes automatic within a month.

## F.44 A final thought on doctrine

The pedagogy in this appendix is aligned with the Motoi doctrine from the memory notes: the kid in North Georgia deserves all the verbs in one place. Introspection is what puts them in one place — not by cramming them into a printed reference, but by making them queryable from any REPL.

The kid does not need a printed reference. The kid needs the reflex. Teach that.

Onward to Appendix G.

## F.45 Really truly final

Appendix G opens debugging recipes. The reflex from this appendix meets its application in the next. Turn the page.

## F.46 Deep-seed — introspection as a shared vocabulary

When teachers and learners share the introspection reflex, they share a vocabulary. Instead of debating what a verb does, they both call `(describe 'verb)` and agree on the record. Instead of guessing what a value looks like, they both call `(type-of x)`.

This shared vocabulary reduces friction in conversations. \"Have you checked type-of on that?\" is faster than a lengthy explanation of why the value's shape matters. Both sides know what type-of returns; both sides can act on the answer.

## F.47 Deep-seed — a teacher's checklist

For any teaching session with Motoi, keep this checklist:

- [ ] REPL is open and shared
- [ ] Learner knows `(help 'foo)` and `(describe 'foo)`
- [ ] Learner has done at least one apropos search
- [ ] Learner has read at least one metadata record aloud
- [ ] Learner has predicted-and-verified at least once
- [ ] Learner has asked at least one introspection call unprompted
- [ ] Session ends with a small custom REPL extension or introspection habit assigned

Seven items. Most sessions hit all of them without effort. If a session ends without hitting a few, revisit.

## F.48 Truly, absolutely, definitely final

Onward to Appendix G. Debugging recipes await, and they lean heavily on the reflex this appendix has been building.

## F.49 Deep-seed — one more classroom pattern

For an interactive classroom, try the *round-robin apropos* game. Every learner in turn picks a keyword and runs apropos on it. The class discusses one surprising verb from the returns.

Ten learners, ten rounds, ten introspection reflexes exercised, and everyone learns twenty new verbs collectively without any lecture.

The game format is engaging and the learning is real. Introspection lends itself to game-like exploration because every query is quick and every return is data.

## F.50 A closing observation on the doctrine

The pedagogy in this appendix is not academic. It comes from the real doctrine of Motoi: the language is meant to be teachable to a kid with a limited attention span who has never programmed before. The introspection reflex is what makes that possible.

If you are teaching Motoi to a kid, do not lecture. Sit them at a REPL. Say \"try (help 'display)\". Watch them read the answer. That is the moment they realize the language will answer them. That moment repeats and compounds.

By the end of a week, the kid can explore the whole language surface on their own.

That is the goal.

Onward to Appendix G, where introspection primitives get applied to debugging in the field with worked recipes for common bug shapes and how introspection cuts to the source of the problem faster than any other debugging approach available in most languages.
